Very much seeing in our company that which Mike is saying . . . from the standpoint of productivity.

But we are expanding our workforce footprint and retaining those who you would classify as having "push-button" roles. 

What is differentiating our business (we are not SaaS though so, I want to qualify that aspect) is that we recognized that button-pushing was going to go away pretty early and instituted both education and on-hands training to upskill our people to be able to evolve by using AI in their work as force-multiplier.

The CEOs can choose to support their existing employees to be more productive through the education, training and use of AI to drive down margins.

So, I agree with the pain that is going to be experienced with white collar push-button jobs . . . but it does not have to be . . .

But then that's the problem when a company views their employees as "Human Resources" rather than "Human Beings" that are able to learn and adapt if given the chance.

Mike Taylor is always a highlight during these Hedgeye Investing Summits . . . straightshooter with lots of insights.
